@NODE "Introduction" "Introduction"
 @{B}Introduction@{UB}

 The Workbench Pattern Injector, also known as WBPI, was written in about 2 hours.  The idea and inspiration came from a fellow IRC'er, who has a problem, and was looking for a solution. Being the nice guy I am, (plus having some WBPattern code already lying around), I wrote WBPI.

 WBPI will take one or more source files. There source files are saved by the OS3.0 prefs program, WBPattern.  One to three of the available targets, screen, Workbench, or drawer window patterns will be then merged into a destination WBPattern file.  The destination file must already exist, tho, and will usually be env:sys/wbpattern.prefs.

 There isn't much more to the program. It's quite simple, but may turn out handy to those who like fancy-pant Workbench screen.  I personally enjoy a plain, grey screen most of the time. :)
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Installation" "Installation"
 @{B}Installation@{UB}

 Simply copy the only useful file of this archive, WBPI, and maybe it's icon, to a location somewhere in your system path.  C: would be a nice location for it.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "CLI_USAGE" "CLI Usage"
 @{B}CLI Usage@{UB}

 The programs template is

 FROM/A,TO,WB=WORKBENCH/S,W=WINDOWS/S,S=SCREEN/ S


 @{FG shine}FROM@{FG text}

  The source .pre file to retreive the new patterns.  This is required. Only one from file is possible, whereas the WB interface accepts multiple files.


 @{FG shine}TO@{FG text}

  An optional, alternative destination file. This defaults to env:sys/wbpattern.prefs.  Note that the WB interface always uses this destination.


 @{FG shine}WORKBENCH, WINDOW, SCREEN@{FG text}

  This specifies which chunks to copy.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "WB_USAGE" "WB Usage"
@NEXT "History"
 @{B}Workbench Usage@{UB}

 WBPI may be used in two different ways from the Workbench interface:

 
 As a default tool from project icons-

  Save the .pre file with WBPattern's "Create Icons?" checked.  Edit the icon using Workbench's Information... window, or a nice program like Iconian @{"" link "Bonus"}. Change the default tool string to point at WBPI executable.  Now, you can add one of the three tooltype discussed below.  Now, double-clicking the icon will make the changes occur.


 As a "passed" icon to WBPI-

  Selecting the .pre icons, then double clicking the WBPI icon will cause WBPI to load the icons just as above.


 The WBPI icon accepts no tooltypes, but .pre icons do.  Placing one or two of the following tooltypes will cause WBPI to copy the corrisponding field to the env:sys/wbpattern.prefs file.

 WINDOWS
 WORKBENCH
 SCREEN


 Note: you cannot change the destination file with the Workbench interface. You must resort to the CLI or scripts for that.


 ACTIONSAVE

  This stores an identical copy in ENVARC:, of both the pattern and font preference files.


 FONT_COLOR=x
 FONT_BACKGROUND=x

 TEXTONLY   | Only draws the text (JAM1)  (Mutually exclusive with the next 2 tooltypes.
 TEXTBACK   | Draw text and background (JAM2)
 COMPLEMENT | Inverts the source (COMPLEMENT)  - Not tested.  Does WB even support this mode?

 INVERSVID    (activates the inversvid bit)

  These modify the font preference file to reflect the new colors.  If a tooltype is omitted, no change to that variable is made.

 

@ENDNODE

