@NODE "HISTORY" "History"
@PREV WB_USAGE
 @{B}History@{UB}

A long, long, long time ago, man was limited to black and green monitors. These monitors only allowed text.  Sometimes the text would flash. Other times it would appear underlined.  But regardless of how it displayed the text, the computer did it's job.  man was happy.

A while later, man discovered graphics.  Of course these graphics were still pretty limited, and consisted of balls, lines, and smiley faces.  But the computer continued to do what it was built for.  man was happy.

After years of the monochrome text with little graphics, the computers gained color.  At this point, the computers could now display all those text files, spreadsheets, and games in colorful text and simple graphics. And the computer continued to do its job.  man was happy.

Soon after, man wanted more.  Charts, games, and pictures still lacked something.  Because of this, computers then gained the ability to draw lines, circles, and squares.  Games and graphic programs quickly took advantage  of these four color displays.  The computer worked on.  man was happy.

At one point in time, some computer had colorful text, some had monochrome graphics, and some still had monochrome text.  But the computer did it's job. man was happy.

During a forgotten period of time, a computer was invented that did all of the above.  True, it did cheat to accomplish some of these feats. But this computer did it's job, and it did them very well.  Several men were quite happy.

Years went by, and the other computers each gained what the others had. Long after the first computer was built, all computers were identically powerful. But with these new powers came a price for the computers.  Colorful text and simple graphics were not enough to satisfy man.  Three dimensional gadgets, colorful icons, detailed scalable text, and 256 color backdrops were all required by man.  Even to do the simple tasks the computers had been doing for years and years. The computers loyally did their jobs.  And although more effort was placed into these new abilities than the actual work, man was happy.  Or was he?

The moral of this story is that enough is never enough.
@ENDNODE

